{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 14:37:22.161675", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and environment\n- Topology: 1 super-spine (AS 65000) connected to 2 spines (AS 65100, 65101). Each spine connects to 2 leaves (AS 65200, 65201). Each leaf connects to a single host:\n  - pc_0_0 behind leaf_router_0_0 (10.0.0.0/24)\n  - pc_0_1 behind leaf_router_0_1 (10.0.1.0/24)\n- Routing protocol: EBGP everywhere (FRR). Inter-router links use 172.16.0.0/16 /31s.\n\nPrimary symptom\n- End-to-end packet loss between hosts. Representative tests:\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 50% packet loss, RTT ~3 ms\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: 50% packet loss, RTT ~2–3 ms\n\nControl-plane status (BGP)\n- All BGP sessions across leaves, spines, and super-spine are established and exchanging routes normally.\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200): Peering with both spines; advertises 10.0.0.0/24; receives 10.0.1.0/24.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201): Peering with both spines; advertises 10.0.1.0/24; receives 10.0.0.0/24.\n  - spines (AS 65100, 65101): Peer with super-spine and both leaves; have best paths to both /24s.\n  - super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000): Peers with both spines; sees both /24s via each spine.\n- show ip bgp on all routers confirms correct best paths for 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24.\n- No signs of flapping, missing prefixes, or adjacency issues.\n\nData-plane and interfaces\n- Links to hosts and between routers are UP at 10 Gbps, full-duplex.\n- Interface statistics on leaf interfaces toward hosts (eth2 on both leaves) and on pc_0_0 (eth0) show:\n  - No errors, no drops, fq_codel qdisc, no congestion indicators.\n- Anomaly on pc_0_1:\n  - eth0 is configured with a netem qdisc: “qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%”\n  - This introduces 60% packet corruption on egress from pc_0_1.\n  - No direct drops reported at the qdisc (consistent with corruption rather than dropping), but corrupted packets are discarded by receivers due to checksum errors.\n\nFault localization\n- The packet loss is present in both directions of ping:\n  - From pc_0_0 to pc_0_1: Echo replies are sent by pc_0_1 and thus subject to its netem corruption, causing lost replies (observed ~50%).\n  - From pc_0_1 to pc_0_0: Echo requests originate from pc_0_1 and are subject to the same corruption, causing lost requests (observed ~50%).\n- Core and leaf devices show healthy counters and no drops/errors; BGP is healthy. This narrows the issue to the host edge.\n- The only device with an active impairment is pc_0_1 (eth0), with a tc netem corruption profile.\n\nAssessment and root cause\n- Anomaly detected: Significant end-to-end packet loss (~50%) between hosts with low RTT and stable control plane.\n- Faulty device: pc_0_1 (host), interface eth0.\n- Root cause: Misconfiguration on pc_0_1 applying tc netem with “corrupt 60%” on the egress qdisc of eth0, causing random packet corruption and effective loss as receivers drop corrupted frames/packets.\n\nImpact\n- Any traffic to or from pc_0_1 experiences intermittent loss consistent with the configured corruption rate.\n- The routing fabric (leaves, spines, super-spine) is functioning correctly; the impairment is localized to pc_0_1’s NIC queueing configuration.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8287, "output_tokens": 2515, "total_tokens": 10802, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 6144}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1600}}}
